ockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In May 1999, research suggested Dolly might be susceptible to premature aging. The possibility that the world's most famous sheep might die early was raised after a study of her genetics. <br>
<br>
A team from the Edinburgh-based biotech company PPL Therapeutics examined structures in Dolly's cells called telomeres. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Telomeres seal the ends of chromosomes in plants and animals much like the plastic tip on the end of a shoelace. Like the plastic tip that wears out allowing the lace to fray and become hard to use, so does the telomere break down in most cells in the human body over time. For about 10 years, scientists have been looking at telomeres in humans for connections to cancer and aging. <br>
<br>
&quot;The integrity of the shoelace is maintained in large part because of this plastic tip,&quot; Shippen said. &quot;In the same way, the telomere provides the stability for the chromosomes through many divisions of the cell.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Telomeres are essential timekeepers for how many times a cell can divide,&quot; she explained. &quot;There's a strong correlation between telomeres and the ability of cancer cells to divide. So, if we can understand what a cell sees in terms of telomere structure and function that allows it to decide if a telomere is functional or not in plants, we hope that will be translatable to understanding how cell division is controlled in humans,&quot; she said. <br>
<br>
===============================================<br>
<br>
I remember reading an article that claimed that if scientists could stop the progressive shortening of the Telomere with each cell division then it may be possible to make someone immortal... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/03 1:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=181.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Imortality</span><hr size=1> Its not so daft, Many animals (reptiles for example) are actually immortal already insofar as they live until something kills them. the trick is that *immortal* animals always keep on growing, *mortal* animals stop growing once they reach maturity.<br>
<br>
The problem with tinkering with telomerines is that there is a significant risk of cancer AIUI.<br>
<br>
I wonder how imortality (Note not *invulnerability*!) would change the way people behave? I am envisaging a situation where people retain the physical condition they had when they were, say, 25 and live untill something kills them (disease, accedent etc) many would die young, as they do now, some however could live centuries or even millenia.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
